1 Introduction

This project was completed by Irina Maruna and Lucas Chapelle for DAT 402.

We use two custom datasets: activities_dakota.csv and activities_lucas.csv. These datasets contain detailed information collected from fitness trackers, covering a variety of workouts such as running, cycling, and walking. Each dataset offers rich features such as distance, duration, calories burned, heart rate metrics, and environmental conditions.

Our primary goal is to predict the number of calories burned during running sessions. We aim to identify which variables (e.g., distance, heart rate, pace) best explain calorie expenditure, using machine learning models like Linear Regression and Ridge Regression.

By combining data from two sources, this project not only increases sample size but also improves the generalizability of the analysis. The final models and results can help support personal training decisions and optimize workout strategies.

4 Data Cleaning & Feature Selection

4.1 Cleaning Dakota’s dataset

dakota_run$Calories <- gsub("[^0-9.]", "", dakota_run$Calories)
# Convert relevant columns to numeric
dakota_clean <- dakota_run %>%
  mutate(
    Distance = as.numeric(Distance),
    Calories = as.numeric(Calories),
    Avg_HR = as.numeric(`Avg HR`),
    Max_HR = as.numeric(`Max HR`)
  )

# Convert Time to total minutes
convert_to_minutes <- function(time_str) {
  parts <- strsplit(time_str, ":")[[1]]
  if (length(parts) == 3) {
    return(as.numeric(parts[1]) * 60 + as.numeric(parts[2]) + as.numeric(parts[3]) / 60)
  } else {
    return(NA)
  }
}

dakota_clean$Time_Minutes <- sapply(dakota_clean$Time, convert_to_minutes)

# Select only needed columns
dakota_clean <- dakota_clean %>%
  select(Distance, Calories, Avg_HR, Max_HR, Time_Minutes) %>%
  mutate(Source = "Dakota")

# Create Pace (min per km)
dakota_clean <- dakota_clean %>%
  mutate(Pace = Time_Minutes / Distance)

# Remove rows with missing values
dakota_clean <- na.omit(dakota_clean)

6 Model Building – Linear Regression

set.seed(42)  # for reproducibility

# Train-test split (70% train, 30% test)
sample_index <- sample(1:nrow(combined_data), size = 0.7 * nrow(combined_data))
train_data <- combined_data[sample_index, ]
test_data  <- combined_data[-sample_index, ]

# Build linear regression model
model_lm <- lm(Calories ~ Distance + Avg_HR + Max_HR + Time_Minutes + Pace, data = train_data)

# View model summary
summary(model_lm)

We built a linear regression model to predict Calories burned using Distance, Avg HR, Max HR, Time (min), and Pace.

Model Performance:

  • R-squared = 0.818. The model explains about 82% of the variance in calories burned, showing a strong fit.
  • Residuals: The median residual is low (~2.17), with some larger values, suggesting a few outliers.

Key Insights:

  • Distance is the most important and statistically significant predictor (p < 0.001). Longer runs burn more calories.
  • Time_Minutes is also significant (p < 0.05), meaning longer duration is a strong calorie predictor.
  • Max_HR is borderline significant (p ia round 0.05), indicating a possible small effect.
  • Avg_HR and Pace are not statistically significant in this model, likely due to collinearity with other variables.

Conclusion: Distance and Time are the most reliable features for predicting calorie burn during runs.

7 Ridge Regression

# Load necessary library
library(glmnet)
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-8
# Prepare data for glmnet (matrices required)
x_train <- as.matrix(train_data[, c("Distance", "Avg_HR", "Max_HR", "Time_Minutes", "Pace")])
y_train <- train_data$Calories

x_test <- as.matrix(test_data[, c("Distance", "Avg_HR", "Max_HR", "Time_Minutes", "Pace")])
y_test <- test_data$Calories

# Ridge regression with cross-validation to choose lambda
set.seed(42)
ridge_cv <- cv.glmnet(x_train, y_train, alpha = 0)

# Optimal lambda
best_lambda <- ridge_cv$lambda.min

# Final model
ridge_model <- glmnet(x_train, y_train, alpha = 0, lambda = best_lambda)

# Predict
ridge_preds <- predict(ridge_model, s = best_lambda, newx = x_test)

# R-squared and RMSE
ridge_r2 <- 1 - sum((y_test - ridge_preds)^2) / sum((y_test - mean(y_test))^2)
ridge_rmse <- sqrt(mean((y_test - ridge_preds)^2))

ridge_r2
## [1] 0.8180744
ridge_rmse
## [1] 144.8884

To evaluate the Ridge Regression model, we used two key performance metrics:

  • R-squared (R^2): 0.818. This means it explained about 81.8% of the variance in calories burned - a strong fit, but slightly lower than the linear model’s performance (R² is around 0.8184).
  • RMSE: 144.89. It indicates that, on average, the model’s calorie predictions were off by about 145 calories. This error is higher than expected and also greater than the linear model’s (around 137.6), suggesting Ridge did not outperform standard linear regression in this case.

This may be because the dataset is already relatively clean and well-structured, and the additional regularization from Ridge did not provide extra benefit. Still, testing Ridge regression is useful for model comparison and reinforces the reliability of the linear model’s results.

We also used two visualizations to assess model performance:

  • Predicted vs Actual Calories: The plot shows that most predictions fall near the reference line, suggesting the model captures general calorie patterns reasonably well. However, some under- and over-prediction is visible, especially for higher calorie values.
  • Residuals vs Predicted Calories: The plot reveals a wider spread of residuals at higher predicted values, and some systematic variation, indicating the model may not fully capture all underlying patterns. This supports the slightly lower performance metrics we saw earlier (R²=0.818, RMSE is around 145), and suggests that while the Ridge model performs decently, it doesn’t improve much over standard linear regression.

9 Cross-Validation with Ridge Regression

# Load required package
library(glmnet)

# Prepare data from the combined and cleaned training set
x <- as.matrix(train_data[, c("Distance", "Avg_HR", "Max_HR", "Time_Minutes", "Pace")])
y <- train_data$Calories

# Perform 10-fold cross-validation for Ridge Regression
set.seed(42)
cv_ridge <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, nfolds = 10)

# Plot cross-validation error vs. lambda
plot(cv_ridge)

# Extract the best lambda
best_lambda <- cv_ridge$lambda.min
best_lambda
## [1] 77.66514

The cross-validation plot shows that our Ridge model achieved the lowest error around log(Lambda) is around 4.6. This value was selected to build our final model. The flat shape around the minimum suggests that the model is stable, and small changes in Lambda won’t significantly impact performance. As Lambda increases beyond this point, the error steadily rises, the model becomes overly simplified, leading to higher prediction errors.

10 Conclusion

  • In this project, we explored and modeled calorie expenditure during running activities using datasets from two sources. After cleaning and combining the data, we analyzed key factors like Distance, Heart Rate, Time, and Pace, all of which showed meaningful relationships with calories burned. We built a Linear Regression model and a Ridge Regression model to predict calories.

  • The Linear Regression model performed slightly better, with an R^2 of 0.818 and a lower prediction error (RMSE around 137.6) compared to Ridge. The Ridge Regression model, while slightly less accurate (R^2 = 0.818, RMSE around 144.9), confirmed that regularization didn’t bring major improvements - likely because the dataset was already clean and variables were not overly complex.

  • Overall, Distance and Time were the most significant predictors, while Pace and Heart Rate added additional insight. The models were reliable, and the analysis revealed consistent patterns between effort and energy burned. This project highlights how structured fitness data can be effectively used to build predictive models and extract practical health insights.
